<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-105-830  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 105 830.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  March 13 1989 v6 n10 p59(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Object-oriented tool promises much, but shipment is delayed.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (marketing)International Business Machines Corp. (marketing)Micro Data Base Systems Inc. (products).andO;Ticker:    IBM; MSFT.andO;Product:   OS/2 Presentation Manager (Graphical user interface) (equipmentand supplies)Object/1 (Program development software).andO;Topic:     Product DelayObject-Oriented LanguagesOS-2Computer graphicsGraphical User Interface.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Add Micro Data Base Systems Inc.'s Object/1 object-oriented developmentlanguage to the list of OS/2 applications missing in action.andM;Announced 15 months ago by Microsoft Corp. and IBM to show thatobject-oriented programming tools and graphical Presentation Managerapplications were just around the corner, Object/1 won't be beta tested untilJune and won't be shipped until the end of December.andP;  It was due to beshipped this month.andM;Micro Data Base Systems (MDBS), based in Lafayette, Ind., describes Object/1as a product designed to help programmers develop database systems or anyother type of object-oriented PM applications.andM;According to Product Manager Gary Christie, Object/1 will free developersfrom the drudgery of creating graphical C applications from scratch toproduce the windows, control buttons, dialogue boxes, menu screens and othergraphical elements that are built into any Presentation Manager application.andM;Object/1 includes a forms painter, database interfaces and suchsoftware-development tools as a source-level debugger and a system browser.andM;Programmers can use the forms painter to build screen displays for PMapplications that include pop-up menus, menu bars and control buttons.andP;  TheSystem Browser lets programmers view and edit the structure of theirapplications as they build them.andM;MDBS plans to offer interfaces to two Structured Query Language (SQL)databases: its own MDBS III and Oracle Corp.'s Oracle.andP;  The company alsoplans to release interfaces to additional databases after the product isshipped.andM;The program is designed to be used by programmers who are developingcommercial or corporate applications for the Presentation Manager.andM;Christie said the main cause of the delay has been the time it has taken ''tobring programmers up to speed in object-oriented programming skills.''andO;Programmers who are trained in object-oriented techniques are scarce, headded.andM;Adding CASE FeaturesandM;MDBS has also decided to use the extra time to add features to Object/1 tomake it more of a full-scale computer-aided software engineering (CASE) tool.andM;It's not surprising that developers are having trouble producingobject-oriented programming tools, said Gene Forte, executive editor andpresident of CASE Outlook, a technical journal published in Portland, Ore.andM;''There is a lot of confusion about what the term 'object-orientedprogramming' means,'' Forte said.andM;Moreover, Forte said, few programmers know how to apply those capabilities.andO;There will be a period of experimentation as MDBS and other developers offerproducts they hope will be accepted as the models for object-orientedprogramming, he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>